/* CISA :: content/quiz4.js — CISA Domain 4 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISA = window.CISA || {}; CISA.questions = CISA.questions || [];
CISA.questions.push.apply(CISA.questions, [
{"id":"D4-001","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is documenting the technology stack of a core banking application. Which component sits BETWEEN the operating system and the application to provide services such as message queuing and transaction management?","options":["Middleware","The database engine","The network firewall","The hypervisor"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Middleware</strong> — middleware is the software layer that connects applications to underlying operating-system and network services, providing message queuing, transaction coordination, and application-integration plumbing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The database engine</b>: stores and retrieves data; it is a back-end resource that middleware may call, not the integration layer itself.</span><span class='qd'><b>The network firewall</b>: filters traffic at the network boundary and provides no application-service brokering.</span><span class='qd'><b>The hypervisor</b>: virtualizes hardware for guest operating systems and sits below the OS, not between the OS and the application.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-002","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"During a data-center walk-through, an IS auditor wants to confirm which device forwards packets between different IP subnets. Which component performs this function?","options":["A layer-2 switch","A router","A network hub","A patch panel"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A router</strong> — a router operates at layer 3 and forwards packets between distinct IP networks or subnets based on routing tables, which is exactly the inter-subnet forwarding described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A layer-2 switch</b>: forwards frames within a single broadcast domain using MAC addresses and does not route between subnets.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network hub</b>: repeats electrical signals to all ports with no addressing intelligence at all.</span><span class='qd'><b>A patch panel</b>: is a passive cabling termination point and performs no forwarding.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-003","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviewing server hardening notes that the operating system controls access to memory, CPU, and I/O for all running processes. Which control objective is MOST directly served by proper OS configuration?","options":["Ensuring application source code is version-controlled","Guaranteeing that batch jobs run in the correct sequence","Enforcing resource isolation and access control among processes","Optimizing the physical cooling of the server room"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Enforcing resource isolation and access control among processes</strong> — the OS kernel mediates access to hardware resources and enforces separation and privilege boundaries between processes, which is the core security service of a properly configured OS.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ensuring application source code is version-controlled</b>: is a software-configuration-management concern handled by development tooling, not the OS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guaranteeing that batch jobs run in the correct sequence</b>: is a scheduler function layered above the OS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Optimizing the physical cooling of the server room</b>: is an environmental facilities control unrelated to OS configuration.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-004","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating controls over a hypervisor hosting 40 production virtual machines. Which risk is MOST specific to this virtualized environment?","options":["Loss of a single physical network cable","Expiration of a single user password","Depletion of printer toner supplies","VM sprawl and compromise of the hypervisor exposing all guests"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>VM sprawl and compromise of the hypervisor exposing all guests</strong> — the hypervisor is a shared control plane, so a breach or misconfiguration there can affect every hosted VM, and uncontrolled provisioning (sprawl) is a virtualization-specific governance risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Loss of a single physical network cable</b>: is a generic availability issue not specific to virtualization.</span><span class='qd'><b>Depletion of printer toner supplies</b>: is an unrelated consumables concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Expiration of a single user password</b>: is a routine identity event, not a virtualization-layer risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-005","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"hard","q":"While reviewing network architecture, an IS auditor finds that load is distributed across multiple web servers by a device that also performs SSL termination. Which component is described?","options":["An intrusion detection sensor","A syslog collector","A load balancer","A tape library"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A load balancer</strong> — a load balancer distributes client requests across a pool of servers and commonly offloads SSL/TLS termination, matching the described behavior.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>An intrusion detection sensor</b>: monitors and alerts on suspicious traffic but does not distribute load.</span><span class='qd'><b>A syslog collector</b>: aggregates log messages and performs no traffic distribution.</span><span class='qd'><b>A tape library</b>: is an offline backup storage device unrelated to web traffic.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-006","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing whether an organization's use of containers is well controlled. Compared with traditional virtual machines, which characteristic of containers introduces the MOST notable control consideration?","options":["Containers each bundle a full guest operating system, increasing patch effort","Containers eliminate the need for any change management","Containers cannot be orchestrated or scaled automatically","Containers share the host OS kernel, so kernel isolation and image integrity are critical"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Containers share the host OS kernel, so kernel isolation and image integrity are critical</strong> — because containers share the host kernel rather than running a full separate OS, weaknesses in namespace isolation or in a compromised base image can affect the host and other containers, making these the key controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Containers each bundle a full guest operating system, increasing patch effort</b>: is false; that describes virtual machines, not containers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Containers cannot be orchestrated or scaled automatically</b>: is incorrect; orchestration platforms are a primary strength of containers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Containers eliminate the need for any change management</b>: is wrong; container images and deployments still require change control.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-007","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor wants to verify that the organization maintains an accurate inventory of hardware and software and the relationships between them. Which repository BEST supports this objective?","options":["The configuration management database (CMDB)","The general ledger","The intrusion prevention rulebase","The email archive"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The configuration management database (CMDB)</strong> — the CMDB records configuration items, their attributes, and relationships, providing the authoritative inventory of IT assets and their dependencies.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The general ledger</b>: records financial transactions and lacks technical configuration relationships.</span><span class='qd'><b>The intrusion prevention rulebase</b>: defines traffic-blocking rules, not an asset inventory.</span><span class='qd'><b>The email archive</b>: stores messages for retention and discovery, not asset data.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-008","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing software licensing. Which condition represents the GREATEST compliance risk?","options":["The organization owns more licenses than it has deployed","Deployed software instances exceed the number of purchased licenses","License records are stored in the CMDB","Vendor maintenance contracts are renewed annually"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Deployed software instances exceed the number of purchased licenses</strong> — using more copies than are licensed is an under-licensing condition that exposes the organization to vendor true-up penalties and legal liability, the greatest compliance risk listed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The organization owns more licenses than it has deployed</b>: represents wasted spend, not a legal compliance breach.</span><span class='qd'><b>License records are stored in the CMDB</b>: is a good practice that supports compliance rather than threatening it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor maintenance contracts are renewed annually</b>: is normal lifecycle activity and not a violation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-009","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"medium","q":"During an asset-management review, an IS auditor finds several servers still in the CMDB that were physically decommissioned months ago. What is the PRIMARY risk of this discrepancy?","options":["Increased software licensing discounts","Reduced electricity consumption","Faster network throughput","Inaccurate inventory undermining patching, capacity, and incident-response decisions"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Inaccurate inventory undermining patching, capacity, and incident-response decisions</strong> — a CMDB that does not reflect reality causes flawed decisions: teams may chase phantom assets or overlook real ones during patching, capacity planning, and incident handling.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increased software licensing discounts</b>: is not a consequence of stale records and is not a risk at all.</span><span class='qd'><b>Faster network throughput</b>: is unrelated to inventory accuracy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reduced electricity consumption</b>: describes a benefit of decommissioning, not a risk of the stale record.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-010","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating the IT asset lifecycle. At which stage should data on storage media be securely sanitized or destroyed?","options":["During disposal/retirement","During deployment","During procurement","During capacity planning"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>During disposal/retirement</strong> — media sanitization or destruction is a disposal-stage control that prevents residual sensitive data from being exposed when an asset leaves the organization's control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>During procurement</b>: precedes any data being stored on the asset, so there is nothing to sanitize.</span><span class='qd'><b>During deployment</b>: is when the asset is placed into service and loaded with data, the opposite of sanitization.</span><span class='qd'><b>During capacity planning</b>: is an analysis activity that does not involve media destruction.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-011","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor wants assurance that the CMDB remains accurate over time. Which control provides the BEST ongoing assurance?","options":["A one-time inventory taken at implementation","Periodic reconciliation of the CMDB against automated discovery scans","Storing the CMDB on encrypted disk","Assigning the CMDB a memorable name"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Periodic reconciliation of the CMDB against automated discovery scans</strong> — comparing recorded configuration items with what discovery tools actually detect on the network identifies drift and keeps the inventory accurate on a continuing basis.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A one-time inventory taken at implementation</b>: becomes stale quickly and provides no ongoing assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing the CMDB on encrypted disk</b>: protects confidentiality but does nothing for accuracy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assigning the CMDB a memorable name</b>: has no bearing on data quality.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-012","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviewing end-of-life management finds business-critical applications running on an operating system the vendor no longer supports. What is the MOST significant audit concern?","options":["The user interface may look outdated","The software cost is fully depreciated","Security patches are no longer issued, leaving known vulnerabilities unremediated","Help-desk staff must learn a new product name"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Security patches are no longer issued, leaving known vulnerabilities unremediated</strong> — once a platform is out of support, newly discovered vulnerabilities will never be patched by the vendor, creating an accumulating and unmitigable exposure, which is the primary concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The user interface may look outdated</b>: is a cosmetic issue, not a material risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The software cost is fully depreciated</b>: is a favorable accounting position, not an audit concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Help-desk staff must learn a new product name</b>: is a trivial operational detail.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-013","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing overnight batch processing. Which tool is PRIMARILY responsible for triggering jobs in the correct order and at the correct times?","options":["A spreadsheet macro","A job scheduler","A print spooler","A DNS server"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A job scheduler</strong> — a job scheduler defines dependencies, calendars, and triggers so that batch jobs run in the proper sequence and at the appropriate times without manual intervention.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet macro</b>: automates cell operations within a workbook, not enterprise batch orchestration.</span><span class='qd'><b>A print spooler</b>: queues documents for printing and does not orchestrate jobs.</span><span class='qd'><b>A DNS server</b>: resolves hostnames to IP addresses and is unrelated to job timing.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-014","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor examines a scheduled job that failed silently overnight, and no one noticed until customers complained. Which control was MOST likely missing?","options":["A larger monitor for the operator","A brighter data-center light","Automated failure alerting and monitoring of job completion","A faster office printer"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Automated failure alerting and monitoring of job completion</strong> — job status monitoring with automatic alerts on abnormal termination ensures failures are detected and acted on promptly rather than surfacing through customer complaints.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A brighter data-center light</b>: has no relationship to detecting job failures.</span><span class='qd'><b>A larger monitor for the operator</b>: does not create alerts or ensure anyone is watching.</span><span class='qd'><b>A faster office printer</b>: is irrelevant to batch monitoring.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-015","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews access to the enterprise job-scheduling tool and finds that application developers can create and modify production schedules directly. What is the PRIMARY concern?","options":["Developers may prefer a different scheduling product","The schedules are stored in UTC time","Scheduling jobs consumes CPU cycles","Lack of segregation of duties allows unauthorized or untested jobs to run in production"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Lack of segregation of duties allows unauthorized or untested jobs to run in production</strong> — when developers control production scheduling, they can execute code without independent operations review, defeating segregation of duties and enabling unauthorized or untested processing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Developers may prefer a different scheduling product</b>: is a preference issue, not a control failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Scheduling jobs consumes CPU cycles</b>: is a normal resource cost, not a governance risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The schedules are stored in UTC time</b>: is a benign configuration detail.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-016","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing batch job dependencies. A downstream reconciliation job started before its upstream extract completed, producing incomplete results. Which scheduler control would have prevented this?","options":["Enforcing job dependency/predecessor conditions before execution","Increasing the print queue size","Assigning the jobs shorter names","Disabling all logging"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Enforcing job dependency/predecessor conditions before execution</strong> — configuring predecessor dependencies ensures a downstream job runs only after its prerequisite jobs complete successfully, preventing processing on incomplete data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing the print queue size</b>: has nothing to do with job sequencing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assigning the jobs shorter names</b>: does not affect execution order.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all logging</b>: would reduce the ability to detect problems, worsening control.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-017","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to confirm that a critical nightly batch job can recover from a mid-run failure without duplicating transactions. Which design feature is MOST relevant?","options":["Checkpoint/restart capability","A colorful job icon","A longer job name","A quieter server fan"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Checkpoint/restart capability</strong> — checkpoint/restart lets a long-running job resume from the last successful checkpoint rather than reprocessing from the start, preventing duplicate transactions after a failure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A colorful job icon</b>: is cosmetic and has no processing effect.</span><span class='qd'><b>A longer job name</b>: does not influence recovery behavior.</span><span class='qd'><b>A quieter server fan</b>: is an environmental detail unrelated to job integrity.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-018","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor observes that operators frequently run production jobs manually, outside the scheduler, to 'catch up' after delays. What is the auditor's GREATEST concern?","options":["Manual runs make the schedule display look tidier","Manual runs bypass dependency, authorization, and logging controls, risking data integrity","Manual runs use less electricity","Manual runs require the operator to be present"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Manual runs bypass dependency, authorization, and logging controls, risking data integrity</strong> — jobs run outside the scheduler skip the built-in predecessor checks, approvals, and automated logging, so integrity and accountability are undermined, which is the auditor's chief concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual runs make the schedule display look tidier</b>: is trivial and not a risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual runs use less electricity</b>: is irrelevant and unquantified.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual runs require the operator to be present</b>: is a staffing observation, not the core control failure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-019","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a business-to-business data exchange that uses standardized structured documents such as purchase orders and invoices. Which technology is being described?","options":["A screen saver","Optical character recognition","Electronic data interchange (EDI)","A spreadsheet pivot table"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Electronic data interchange (EDI)</strong> — EDI exchanges standardized structured business documents (orders, invoices, shipping notices) between trading partners in machine-readable format, exactly as described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Optical character recognition</b>: converts images of text to characters and is not a partner-to-partner document standard.</span><span class='qd'><b>A screen saver</b>: is a display utility unrelated to data exchange.</span><span class='qd'><b>A spreadsheet pivot table</b>: summarizes data within a workbook, not between organizations.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-020","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating controls over an automated interface that transfers files between two applications. Which control BEST ensures that no records are lost or duplicated in transit?","options":["Compressing the files before transfer","Using a faster network switch","Renaming the interface files daily","Reconciliation of record counts and control totals between source and target"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Reconciliation of record counts and control totals between source and target</strong> — comparing counts and control totals on both ends detects any records that were dropped, added, or duplicated during transfer, directly assuring completeness and accuracy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Using a faster network switch</b>: improves speed but does not verify completeness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renaming the interface files daily</b>: is a housekeeping step that does not detect lost records.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compressing the files before transfer</b>: reduces size but provides no integrity assurance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-021","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews an API-based integration between an order system and a payment gateway. Which control is MOST important to protect data exchanged over the API?","options":["Storing API logs in a spreadsheet","Displaying the API results in a larger font","Authentication and encryption of API calls (for example, TLS and tokens)","Assigning the API a short URL"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Authentication and encryption of API calls (for example, TLS and tokens)</strong> — authenticating callers and encrypting the channel protect the confidentiality and integrity of sensitive payment data moving across the API, the paramount control for this integration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Displaying the API results in a larger font</b>: is a presentation detail with no security value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing API logs in a spreadsheet</b>: does not protect data in transit and is a weak logging approach.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assigning the API a short URL</b>: has no bearing on data protection.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-022","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that an interface between two systems has no error-handling routine; when a record fails validation it is silently dropped. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The interface will run faster","Users will receive too many alerts","The source system will use more memory","Incomplete data in the target system leading to inaccurate processing and reporting"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Incomplete data in the target system leading to inaccurate processing and reporting</strong> — silently discarding failed records means the target is missing data with no trace, producing inaccurate downstream processing and reports, the principal risk of absent error handling.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The interface will run faster</b>: is not a risk and is an irrelevant side effect.</span><span class='qd'><b>The source system will use more memory</b>: is unrelated to dropped records.</span><span class='qd'><b>Users will receive too many alerts</b>: is the opposite of the problem, since no alerts are generated.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-023","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews middleware used to route messages between a dozen applications. What is the PRIMARY availability concern with this architecture?","options":["The middleware may become a single point of failure affecting all connected systems","The middleware requires a product license","Messages are formatted in XML","The middleware has a technical name"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The middleware may become a single point of failure affecting all connected systems</strong> — because many applications depend on the message bus, an outage of the middleware can disrupt every connected system, making single-point-of-failure the key availability concern.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The middleware requires a product license</b>: is a normal commercial condition, not an availability risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Messages are formatted in XML</b>: is a format choice with no bearing on availability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The middleware has a technical name</b>: is irrelevant.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-024","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is testing an EDI environment. Which control provides the BEST assurance that inbound trading-partner transactions are authorized and have not been altered?","options":["Functional acknowledgments confirming receipt","Digital signatures or message authentication combined with agreed authorization limits","A faster VPN tunnel","Sorting transactions alphabetically"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Digital signatures or message authentication combined with agreed authorization limits</strong> — cryptographic authentication proves origin and integrity, while pre-agreed authorization limits ensure the transaction is within permitted bounds, together assuring inbound EDI messages are genuine and unaltered.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Functional acknowledgments confirming receipt</b>: confirm a message arrived but do not prove authorization or detect content tampering.</span><span class='qd'><b>A faster VPN tunnel</b>: improves throughput, not authenticity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sorting transactions alphabetically</b>: has no control value.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-025","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor learns that a finance team built and relies on a complex spreadsheet to calculate regulatory capital, outside of IT's control. This is an example of:","options":["A hypervisor cluster","A mainframe batch job","A network intrusion","End-user computing (EUC)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>End-user computing (EUC)</strong> — applications such as business-critical spreadsheets developed and maintained by users rather than IT are classic end-user computing, which the auditor must evaluate for adequate controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A mainframe batch job</b>: is centrally managed IT processing, the opposite of user-built tools.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network intrusion</b>: is a security event, not a computing category.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hypervisor cluster</b>: is virtualization infrastructure, unrelated to a user spreadsheet.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-026","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is concerned about shadow IT. Which situation BEST illustrates shadow IT?","options":["A department subscribes to a cloud service without IT or security approval","IT deploys a patch during the approved maintenance window","The CMDB is reconciled with discovery scans","The help desk logs an incident ticket"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A department subscribes to a cloud service without IT or security approval</strong> — shadow IT is technology procured and used outside the sanctioned IT governance process, and an unapproved cloud subscription is a textbook example.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>IT deploys a patch during the approved maintenance window</b>: is a governed, sanctioned activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The CMDB is reconciled with discovery scans</b>: is a legitimate control practice.</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk logs an incident ticket</b>: is a standard managed process.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-027","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating controls over a business-critical spreadsheet. Which control BEST reduces the risk of undetected formula errors?","options":["Choosing a bright font color for totals","Independent review and validation of formulas plus cell protection","Saving the file with a longer name","Emailing the file more frequently"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Independent review and validation of formulas plus cell protection</strong> — having someone other than the author verify the logic, combined with locking cells that hold formulas, directly reduces the chance that a calculation error goes undetected.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Choosing a bright font color for totals</b>: is cosmetic and does not validate correctness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Saving the file with a longer name</b>: has no effect on formula accuracy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Emailing the file more frequently</b>: increases version confusion without validating logic.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-028","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that a key EUC spreadsheet has no version control and multiple users edit copies emailed among themselves. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The spreadsheet consumes disk space","The spreadsheet opens slowly","Use of an outdated or incorrect version leading to erroneous decisions","The file is stored in the cloud"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Use of an outdated or incorrect version leading to erroneous decisions</strong> — without version control and a single authoritative copy, users may unknowingly work from stale or conflicting versions, causing decisions based on wrong numbers.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The spreadsheet consumes disk space</b>: is negligible and not the core risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The spreadsheet opens slowly</b>: is a performance nuisance, not a data-integrity issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>The file is stored in the cloud</b>: is a location detail, not inherently the version risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-029","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is assessing organizational exposure to shadow IT. Which is the MOST significant governance risk?","options":["Users learn new tools quickly","Sensitive data may be processed in unvetted services outside security oversight","The IT budget is fully spent","Vendors offer free trials"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Sensitive data may be processed in unvetted services outside security oversight</strong> — shadow IT can move regulated or confidential data into systems that were never assessed for security or compliance, creating unmanaged data-protection exposure, the most significant governance risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Users learn new tools quickly</b>: is a potential benefit, not a risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The IT budget is fully spent</b>: is a budgeting matter unrelated to shadow IT exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendors offer free trials</b>: is a marketing feature, not a governance risk in itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-030","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is recommending an approach to bring shadow IT under governance. Which recommendation is MOST effective as a FIRST step?","options":["Immediately block all unknown cloud services at the firewall","Ignore shadow IT because users prefer it","Discover and inventory unsanctioned services, then risk-assess and formalize or retire them","Require users to stop using computers entirely"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Discover and inventory unsanctioned services, then risk-assess and formalize or retire them</strong> — you cannot govern what you cannot see, so establishing visibility and assessing risk first enables informed decisions to sanction, secure, or decommission each service.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately block all unknown cloud services at the firewall</b>: can disrupt legitimate business and drives usage further underground before risks are understood.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore shadow IT because users prefer it</b>: abandons governance entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Require users to stop using computers entirely</b>: is unrealistic and not a control.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-031","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing capacity management. What is the PRIMARY objective of the capacity management process?","options":["To negotiate office leases","To delete old email","To design the corporate logo","To ensure IT resources meet current and future business demand cost-effectively"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To ensure IT resources meet current and future business demand cost-effectively</strong> — capacity management forecasts demand and provisions resources so services perform adequately now and in the future without overspending, which is its central goal.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To delete old email</b>: is a data-retention housekeeping task, not capacity management.</span><span class='qd'><b>To design the corporate logo</b>: is a marketing activity unrelated to IT capacity.</span><span class='qd'><b>To negotiate office leases</b>: is a facilities function, not IT resource planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-032","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor examines availability metrics for a service quoted at 99.9% uptime. This metric MOST directly measures:","options":["The proportion of time the service is operational and accessible","The number of employees in IT","The color scheme of the dashboard","The size of the source-code repository"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The proportion of time the service is operational and accessible</strong> — an availability percentage expresses the share of agreed service time during which the service was usable, which is precisely what 99.9% uptime denotes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of employees in IT</b>: is a staffing figure, not availability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color scheme of the dashboard</b>: is a presentation detail.</span><span class='qd'><b>The size of the source-code repository</b>: measures code volume, not uptime.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-033","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor notes that a service repeatedly breaches performance targets during month-end peaks. Which capacity management practice would BEST address this?","options":["Trend analysis and workload forecasting to provision for peak demand","Turning the servers off at night","Reducing the number of monitored metrics","Removing the performance targets"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Trend analysis and workload forecasting to provision for peak demand</strong> — analyzing usage trends and modeling peak workloads lets the organization provision or scale resources ahead of predictable spikes such as month-end, preventing recurring breaches.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Turning the servers off at night</b>: reduces available capacity and worsens performance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reducing the number of monitored metrics</b>: hides the problem rather than solving it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing the performance targets</b>: eliminates the measure of success rather than meeting it.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-034","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing whether monitoring supports availability objectives. Which control is MOST useful for detecting capacity problems before they cause outages?","options":["Annual review of the office floor plan","Threshold-based alerts on resource utilization (CPU, memory, disk, bandwidth)","A quarterly newsletter","Manually reading logs once a year"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Threshold-based alerts on resource utilization (CPU, memory, disk, bandwidth)</strong> — configuring alerts to fire when utilization crosses defined thresholds gives early warning of resource exhaustion so teams can act before an outage occurs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Annual review of the office floor plan</b>: has nothing to do with IT resource utilization.</span><span class='qd'><b>A quarterly newsletter</b>: does not provide real-time capacity signals.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manually reading logs once a year</b>: is far too infrequent to prevent outages.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-035","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews an environment that automatically adds compute resources when demand rises and removes them when demand falls. This capability is BEST described as:","options":["A print queue","A manual reboot procedure","Elastic/auto-scaling capacity","A password policy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Elastic/auto-scaling capacity</strong> — automatically provisioning and de-provisioning resources in response to demand is elasticity or auto-scaling, a key modern capacity-management capability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A manual reboot procedure</b>: is an operator action, not automatic scaling.</span><span class='qd'><b>A print queue</b>: buffers print jobs and is unrelated to compute scaling.</span><span class='qd'><b>A password policy</b>: governs credentials, not capacity.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-036","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds capacity planning is done reactively only after users report slowness. What is the MOST significant weakness of this approach?","options":["It looks unprofessional in reports","It requires forecasting skills","It uses too much monitoring software","Resource shortfalls are addressed only after service degradation, harming availability and SLAs"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Resource shortfalls are addressed only after service degradation, harming availability and SLAs</strong> — purely reactive capacity management means problems are fixed after users are already impacted, so service levels are breached before any action is taken, undermining availability commitments.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It looks unprofessional in reports</b>: is a presentation concern, not the substantive risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>It uses too much monitoring software</b>: reactive planning typically uses less, not more, monitoring.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires forecasting skills</b>: describes proactive planning, which is the desired state, not a weakness.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-037","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"easy","q":"Applying ITIL concepts, an IS auditor asks what the PRIMARY objective of incident management is. Which answer is correct?","options":["To approve changes to production","To identify the underlying root cause of recurring issues","To restore normal service operation as quickly as possible","To design the enterprise architecture"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To restore normal service operation as quickly as possible</strong> — incident management focuses on rapidly restoring service and minimizing business impact, whereas eliminating underlying causes is the domain of problem management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To identify the underlying root cause of recurring issues</b>: is the objective of problem management, not incident management.</span><span class='qd'><b>To approve changes to production</b>: is the role of change management.</span><span class='qd'><b>To design the enterprise architecture</b>: is an architecture activity, not incident handling.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-038","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor distinguishes problems from incidents. What is a 'problem' in this context?","options":["An approved change request","A single user calling the help desk","A scheduled maintenance window","The underlying cause of one or more incidents"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The underlying cause of one or more incidents</strong> — a problem is the root cause behind recurring or significant incidents, and problem management seeks to identify and remove it to prevent recurrence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single user calling the help desk</b>: describes an individual incident report, not the underlying cause.</span><span class='qd'><b>A scheduled maintenance window</b>: is a planned change activity.</span><span class='qd'><b>An approved change request</b>: is an authorization artifact, not a root cause.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-039","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor observes that the same network outage recurs monthly and is resolved each time by rebooting a device, but the cause is never investigated. Which process is deficient?","options":["Problem management","Capacity forecasting","Media rotation","License management"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Problem management</strong> — repeatedly applying a workaround without investigating and removing the root cause indicates problem management is not functioning, since its purpose is to eliminate recurring incidents.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Capacity forecasting</b>: addresses resource demand, not root-cause elimination of a recurring fault.</span><span class='qd'><b>Media rotation</b>: concerns backup tape handling, unrelated to the outage.</span><span class='qd'><b>License management</b>: tracks software entitlements, not incident causes.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-040","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews incident handling and finds no severity/priority classification scheme. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The help desk will run out of ticket numbers","High-impact incidents may not receive appropriately fast response and escalation","Users will type faster","The network will use more bandwidth"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>High-impact incidents may not receive appropriately fast response and escalation</strong> — without prioritization, critical incidents can be queued behind trivial ones, delaying response and escalation for the issues that matter most.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk will run out of ticket numbers</b>: is not a realistic consequence of missing prioritization.</span><span class='qd'><b>Users will type faster</b>: is nonsensical in this context.</span><span class='qd'><b>The network will use more bandwidth</b>: is unrelated to incident classification.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-041","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"hard","q":"After a major outage, an IS auditor evaluates the post-incident review. Which outcome BEST demonstrates that problem management added value?","options":["A new server was purchased for unrelated reasons","The incident ticket was closed within one hour","The help desk answered more calls that day","A known error was documented and a permanent fix eliminated the recurring cause"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A known error was documented and a permanent fix eliminated the recurring cause</strong> — problem management delivers value by finding the root cause, recording it as a known error, and implementing a permanent fix so the incident does not recur.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The incident ticket was closed within one hour</b>: reflects incident-management speed, not root-cause elimination.</span><span class='qd'><b>The help desk answered more calls that day</b>: is a volume metric unrelated to the underlying fix.</span><span class='qd'><b>A new server was purchased for unrelated reasons</b>: does not demonstrate any link to the incident's cause.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-042","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor wants to assess the effectiveness of incident management. Which metric is MOST relevant?","options":["Mean time to restore service (MTTR)","Number of coffee breaks per operator","Length of the server power cable","Font size used in the ticketing tool"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Mean time to restore service (MTTR)</strong> — because incident management aims to restore service quickly, the average time to resolve incidents is a direct and relevant measure of its effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Number of coffee breaks per operator</b>: has no bearing on service restoration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Length of the server power cable</b>: is a physical detail unrelated to incident performance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Font size used in the ticketing tool</b>: is a cosmetic setting.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-043","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing the change management process. Which body is PRIMARILY responsible for reviewing and authorizing significant changes before they are deployed to production?","options":["The catering committee","The change advisory board (CAB)","The physical security guards","The marketing department"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The change advisory board (CAB)</strong> — the CAB reviews, assesses risk, and authorizes significant changes, providing the governance checkpoint before deployment to production.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The catering committee</b>: has no role in IT change governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical security guards</b>: control facility access, not software or infrastructure changes.</span><span class='qd'><b>The marketing department</b>: promotes products and does not authorize technical changes.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-044","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a change that was deployed and then caused an outage. Which control allows the environment to be returned to its prior working state?","options":["A longer lunch break","A louder alarm bell","A documented and tested back-out (rollback) plan","A brighter status light"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A documented and tested back-out (rollback) plan</strong> — a back-out plan defines the steps to reverse a change and restore the previous stable state when a deployment fails, limiting the duration of the outage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A louder alarm bell</b>: may raise awareness but does nothing to restore the prior state.</span><span class='qd'><b>A longer lunch break</b>: is irrelevant to recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>A brighter status light</b>: is cosmetic and provides no rollback capability.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-045","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that the same person develops code, approves the change, and deploys it to production with no independent review. Which principle is violated?","options":["Data normalization","Segregation of duties","Load balancing","RAID striping"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Segregation of duties</strong> — allowing one individual to develop, approve, and deploy without independent oversight concentrates incompatible functions and violates segregation of duties, enabling unauthorized or erroneous changes to reach production undetected.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data normalization</b>: is a database design technique, unrelated to change approvals.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancing</b>: distributes traffic and has nothing to do with duty separation.</span><span class='qd'><b>RAID striping</b>: is a disk-performance arrangement, not a change control.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-046","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing emergency changes. Which control BEST balances the need for speed with accountability?","options":["Letting anyone make emergency changes with no record","Prohibiting all emergency changes under every circumstance","Allowing emergency changes but requiring expedited documented approval and retrospective CAB review","Deferring every emergency to the next quarterly release"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Allowing emergency changes but requiring expedited documented approval and retrospective CAB review</strong> — a defined emergency-change procedure permits rapid action to resolve urgent issues while still requiring authorization and after-the-fact CAB review to preserve accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Prohibiting all emergency changes under every circumstance</b>: is unrealistic and can prolong critical outages.</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting anyone make emergency changes with no record</b>: abandons control and accountability entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deferring every emergency to the next quarterly release</b>: ignores the urgency that defines an emergency change.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-047","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is assessing patch management. Which practice BEST reduces the risk that a patch itself disrupts production?","options":["Applying patches only to printers","Applying every patch to production immediately upon release","Never applying patches at all","Testing patches in a non-production environment before deployment"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Testing patches in a non-production environment before deployment</strong> — validating patches in a representative test environment first surfaces compatibility and stability problems before they can affect production systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Applying every patch to production immediately upon release</b>: skips testing and risks introducing defects into production.</span><span class='qd'><b>Never applying patches at all</b>: leaves known vulnerabilities unremediated.</span><span class='qd'><b>Applying patches only to printers</b>: ignores the systems that matter most.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-048","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews configuration management and finds no baseline of approved configurations. What is the PRIMARY consequence?","options":["Unauthorized configuration drift cannot be reliably detected","The servers will overheat","The network cable will shorten","The database will normalize itself"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Unauthorized configuration drift cannot be reliably detected</strong> — without an approved configuration baseline to compare against, the organization cannot tell when a system has deviated from its authorized state, so drift and unauthorized changes go unnoticed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The servers will overheat</b>: is an environmental issue unrelated to configuration baselines.</span><span class='qd'><b>The network cable will shorten</b>: is physically nonsensical.</span><span class='qd'><b>The database will normalize itself</b>: is not a real consequence of a missing baseline.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-049","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor examines the change log and finds several production changes with no corresponding approved change record. What should the auditor conclude and recommend FIRST?","options":["Unauthorized changes occurred; investigate and strengthen enforcement of the change process","The changes are automatically fine because production still runs","Change records are optional for production","The auditor should delete the log to avoid confusion"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Unauthorized changes occurred; investigate and strengthen enforcement of the change process</strong> — production changes without approval records indicate the change-control process is being bypassed, so the auditor should treat them as unauthorized, investigate, and recommend stronger enforcement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The changes are automatically fine because production still runs</b>: confuses the absence of an immediate failure with the absence of risk or control breach.</span><span class='qd'><b>Change records are optional for production</b>: contradicts the purpose of change management.</span><span class='qd'><b>The auditor should delete the log to avoid confusion</b>: is destruction of evidence and wholly improper.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-050","domain":4,"obj":"4A8","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews source-code control for application changes. Which capability is MOST important to ensure that only reviewed, approved code reaches production?","options":["A faster office coffee machine","Version control with controlled branching, merge approval, and traceability to change requests","A larger developer monitor","A shorter repository name"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Version control with controlled branching, merge approval, and traceability to change requests</strong> — a version-control system that requires approvals to merge and links commits to authorized change requests ensures only reviewed code is promoted and provides an audit trail.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A faster office coffee machine</b>: has no effect on code governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A larger developer monitor</b>: aids comfort but does not control code promotion.</span><span class='qd'><b>A shorter repository name</b>: is irrelevant to approval workflow.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-051","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing operational logging. What is the PRIMARY purpose of enabling and retaining system and security logs?","options":["To slow down the servers deliberately","To increase disk usage for its own sake","To support detection, investigation, and accountability for events","To replace the need for backups"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To support detection, investigation, and accountability for events</strong> — logs provide the evidence needed to detect anomalies, investigate incidents, and hold users and processes accountable, which is the core reason to enable and retain them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To increase disk usage for its own sake</b>: is a side effect, not a purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>To slow down the servers deliberately</b>: is not an objective of logging.</span><span class='qd'><b>To replace the need for backups</b>: is false; logs and backups serve different purposes.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-052","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor notes that a SIEM aggregates logs from many sources. What is the PRIMARY benefit of a SIEM in log management?","options":["Encrypting the office Wi-Fi password","Automatic deletion of all logs each night","Preventing any user from logging in","Centralized correlation and alerting across disparate log sources"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Centralized correlation and alerting across disparate log sources</strong> — a SIEM collects logs from many systems and correlates them to detect patterns and raise alerts that would be invisible when logs are viewed in isolation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Automatic deletion of all logs each night</b>: would destroy the evidence a SIEM is meant to analyze.</span><span class='qd'><b>Preventing any user from logging in</b>: is an access-control action, not a SIEM function.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting the office Wi-Fi password</b>: is unrelated to log correlation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-053","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that logs are collected but never reviewed. What is the PRIMARY weakness?","options":["The logs are too well organized","The logs take up too little space","Collected logs provide no value if suspicious activity is never detected or acted upon","The logs are stored in chronological order"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Collected logs provide no value if suspicious activity is never detected or acted upon</strong> — logging is only effective when combined with review or automated alerting; unreviewed logs do not enable detection or response, defeating their purpose.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The logs take up too little space</b>: is not a weakness and is likely false.</span><span class='qd'><b>The logs are too well organized</b>: would be a strength, not a weakness.</span><span class='qd'><b>The logs are stored in chronological order</b>: is a normal, helpful attribute.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-054","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is concerned that a privileged user could alter logs to hide malicious activity. Which control BEST protects log integrity?","options":["Deleting logs after each shift","Storing logs only on the same server that generates them","Letting administrators edit logs freely","Forwarding logs in near real time to a separate, write-once/append-only repository"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Forwarding logs in near real time to a separate, write-once/append-only repository</strong> — shipping logs off the originating host to tamper-resistant storage that administrators cannot alter preserves their integrity even if the source system is compromised.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing logs only on the same server that generates them</b>: lets a privileged attacker on that host delete or edit the evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Letting administrators edit logs freely</b>: directly defeats integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting logs after each shift</b>: destroys the record needed for investigation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-055","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews log retention. Which factor should PRIMARILY drive the log-retention period?","options":["Legal, regulatory, and investigative requirements","The color of the log console","The brand of the servers","The number of parking spaces at the office"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Legal, regulatory, and investigative requirements</strong> — retention periods must satisfy applicable laws, regulations, and the practical needs of investigations, which are the governing considerations for how long logs are kept.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The color of the log console</b>: is cosmetic and irrelevant.</span><span class='qd'><b>The brand of the servers</b>: does not determine retention obligations.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of parking spaces at the office</b>: is entirely unrelated.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-056","domain":4,"obj":"4A9","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor evaluates time synchronization across logging systems. Why is accurate, synchronized time MOST important for log management?","options":["It makes the logs a smaller file size","It enables reliable correlation and sequencing of events across systems during investigations","It changes the server's IP address","It improves the office clock display"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It enables reliable correlation and sequencing of events across systems during investigations</strong> — consistent, synchronized timestamps (for example via NTP) let investigators accurately order and correlate events across multiple systems, which is essential to reconstruct an incident.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It makes the logs a smaller file size</b>: is untrue; time sync does not affect size.</span><span class='qd'><b>It changes the server's IP address</b>: is unrelated to timekeeping.</span><span class='qd'><b>It improves the office clock display</b>: is a trivial, irrelevant effect.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-057","domain":4,"obj":"4A10","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing service-level management. What does a service level agreement (SLA) PRIMARILY define?","options":["The physical color of the servers","The office dress code","The brand of coffee in the break room","The agreed service targets between a provider and its customer"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The agreed service targets between a provider and its customer</strong> — an SLA documents the measurable service commitments (such as availability and response times) agreed between the provider and the customer, forming the basis for performance measurement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The office dress code</b>: is an HR policy, not a service commitment.</span><span class='qd'><b>The brand of coffee in the break room</b>: is irrelevant to service levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical color of the servers</b>: has nothing to do with service targets.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-058","domain":4,"obj":"4A10","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is clarifying ITIL agreement types. Which agreement covers commitments between internal teams that support an external SLA?","options":["An operational level agreement (OLA)","A software license","A building lease","A purchase order"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>An operational level agreement (OLA)</strong> — an OLA defines the internal support commitments between teams within the same organization that together enable delivery of the customer-facing SLA.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A software license</b>: grants usage rights, not internal support commitments.</span><span class='qd'><b>A building lease</b>: is a real-estate contract.</span><span class='qd'><b>A purchase order</b>: authorizes a procurement, not internal service levels.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-059","domain":4,"obj":"4A10","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing agreements that support an SLA. Which agreement governs commitments made by an EXTERNAL third-party supplier?","options":["An operational level agreement (OLA)","An underpinning contract (UC)","A departmental memo","A staff handbook"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An underpinning contract (UC)</strong> — an underpinning contract is the agreement with an external supplier whose services support the delivery of the customer SLA, and it must align with the SLA targets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>An operational level agreement (OLA)</b>: governs internal teams, not external suppliers.</span><span class='qd'><b>A departmental memo</b>: is informal internal communication, not a binding supplier commitment.</span><span class='qd'><b>A staff handbook</b>: sets employee policy, not supplier service levels.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-060","domain":4,"obj":"4A10","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that SLA performance is reported by the service provider but never independently verified by the customer. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The provider will lower its prices automatically","The reports use too much paper","Reported performance may be inaccurate or self-serving, masking breaches","The customer will receive fewer emails"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Reported performance may be inaccurate or self-serving, masking breaches</strong> — when only the provider measures and reports its own performance without independent validation, the customer cannot be sure the figures are accurate, and genuine breaches may be hidden.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The reports use too much paper</b>: is a trivial concern unrelated to assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The provider will lower its prices automatically</b>: does not follow from unverified reporting.</span><span class='qd'><b>The customer will receive fewer emails</b>: is irrelevant to SLA assurance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-061","domain":4,"obj":"4A10","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor reviews an SLA and finds targets that are not measurable (for example, 'good performance'). What is the PRIMARY problem?","options":["The SLA document is too short","Non-measurable targets cannot be objectively monitored or enforced","The SLA is written in a common language","The SLA has a title page"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Non-measurable targets cannot be objectively monitored or enforced</strong> — SLA commitments must be specific and quantifiable so performance can be measured against them; vague targets provide no objective basis for monitoring or holding the provider accountable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The SLA document is too short</b>: length is not the issue; measurability is.</span><span class='qd'><b>The SLA is written in a common language</b>: clarity is desirable, not a problem.</span><span class='qd'><b>The SLA has a title page</b>: is an inconsequential formatting detail.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-062","domain":4,"obj":"4A10","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing whether SLA monitoring drives improvement. Which practice BEST demonstrates mature service-level management?","options":["Measuring only metrics that are always green","Signing the SLA once and never reviewing it again","Regular service reviews that track SLA trends and trigger corrective action on breaches","Renaming the SLA each year"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Regular service reviews that track SLA trends and trigger corrective action on breaches</strong> — mature service-level management continuously monitors performance, reviews trends with stakeholders, and drives corrective and improvement actions when targets are missed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Signing the SLA once and never reviewing it again</b>: is static and cannot drive improvement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Measuring only metrics that are always green</b>: is cherry-picking that hides real performance issues.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renaming the SLA each year</b>: is a cosmetic change with no substance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-063","domain":4,"obj":"4A11","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing database controls. What is the PRIMARY responsibility of the database administrator (DBA)?","options":["To approve travel expenses","To write the corporate marketing plan","To physically guard the building entrance","To manage the design, integrity, performance, and security of the database"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To manage the design, integrity, performance, and security of the database</strong> — the DBA is responsible for maintaining database structure, integrity, availability, performance tuning, and access controls, which are the core custodial duties over the data store.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To write the corporate marketing plan</b>: is a business function outside the DBA role.</span><span class='qd'><b>To physically guard the building entrance</b>: is a facilities-security task.</span><span class='qd'><b>To approve travel expenses</b>: is an administrative finance function.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-064","domain":4,"obj":"4A11","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing database design. What does normalization PRIMARILY aim to reduce?","options":["Data redundancy and the anomalies it causes","The number of users allowed to log in","The physical size of the server rack","The brightness of the monitor"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Data redundancy and the anomalies it causes</strong> — normalization organizes data to minimize duplication and the insertion, update, and deletion anomalies that redundancy produces, improving integrity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of users allowed to log in</b>: is an access-control matter, not a design goal of normalization.</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical size of the server rack</b>: is unrelated to logical data design.</span><span class='qd'><b>The brightness of the monitor</b>: is a display setting.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-065","domain":4,"obj":"4A11","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is evaluating controls over concurrent database transactions. Which mechanism PRIMARILY prevents two transactions from corrupting data when updating the same record at once?","options":["Locking and concurrency control","Screen-saver activation","Toner replacement","Cable labeling"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Locking and concurrency control</strong> — database locking and concurrency-control mechanisms serialize or coordinate simultaneous access so that concurrent transactions do not overwrite each other and leave data in an inconsistent state.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Screen-saver activation</b>: is a display feature with no effect on transactions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Toner replacement</b>: is a printer-maintenance task.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cable labeling</b>: is a housekeeping practice unrelated to concurrency.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-066","domain":4,"obj":"4A11","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor finds that the DBA has unrestricted access to modify production data directly and also administers the audit logs. What is the PRIMARY concern?","options":["The database will run more slowly","The DBA could make and conceal unauthorized data changes with no independent trail","The data will normalize automatically","The server will need more cooling"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The DBA could make and conceal unauthorized data changes with no independent trail</strong> — combining the ability to alter production data with control over the audit logs lets the DBA both commit and hide improper changes, so the logging must be independent of the DBA to preserve accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The database will run more slowly</b>: is a performance issue unrelated to this segregation risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The data will normalize automatically</b>: is not a real consequence.</span><span class='qd'><b>The server will need more cooling</b>: is an environmental non sequitur.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-067","domain":4,"obj":"4A11","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is verifying referential integrity in a relational database. Which control ENFORCES that a child record cannot reference a non-existent parent?","options":["A longer table name","A brighter query editor","Foreign-key constraints","A faster keyboard"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Foreign-key constraints</strong> — foreign-key constraints enforce referential integrity by rejecting child rows whose referenced parent key does not exist, keeping relationships between tables consistent.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A brighter query editor</b>: is a cosmetic tool setting.</span><span class='qd'><b>A longer table name</b>: does not enforce any relationship.</span><span class='qd'><b>A faster keyboard</b>: is unrelated to data integrity.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-068","domain":4,"obj":"4A11","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is assessing database recovery. After a crash, which combination BEST allows the DBMS to restore committed transactions and undo incomplete ones?","options":["Reinstalling the office suite","Rebooting the desktop client","Clearing the browser cache","Restoring a backup and applying transaction logs (roll-forward and rollback)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Restoring a backup and applying transaction logs (roll-forward and rollback)</strong> — recovery restores the last good backup, then replays committed transactions from the logs (roll-forward) and reverses incomplete ones (rollback) to return the database to a consistent state.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rebooting the desktop client</b>: affects a user workstation, not database recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Clearing the browser cache</b>: has no effect on the DBMS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reinstalling the office suite</b>: is unrelated to database integrity recovery.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-069","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a business impact analysis (BIA). What does the recovery time objective (RTO) define?","options":["The number of employees in the department","The maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time","The maximum acceptable time to restore a process after a disruption","The cost of the office lease"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The maximum acceptable time to restore a process after a disruption</strong> — the RTO is the target elapsed time within which a process or system must be recovered to avoid unacceptable consequences, a key BIA output.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time</b>: describes the recovery point objective (RPO), not the RTO.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of employees in the department</b>: is a staffing figure, not a recovery metric.</span><span class='qd'><b>The cost of the office lease</b>: is a facilities expense unrelated to recovery timing.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-070","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing a BIA. What does the recovery point objective (RPO) define?","options":["The number of backup tapes owned","The maximum time allowed to restore a system","The physical distance to the recovery site","The maximum acceptable amount of data loss expressed as a point in time"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The maximum acceptable amount of data loss expressed as a point in time</strong> — the RPO defines how much data, measured back in time from the disruption, the organization can afford to lose, which drives backup frequency.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The maximum time allowed to restore a system</b>: describes the RTO, not the RPO.</span><span class='qd'><b>The physical distance to the recovery site</b>: is a site-selection factor, not a data-loss metric.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of backup tapes owned</b>: is an inventory count, not an objective.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-071","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a BIA where a system's RTO is set shorter than the time the current backup-and-restore strategy can actually achieve. What is the PRIMARY concern?","options":["The recovery strategy cannot meet the stated objective, so the RTO is unrealistic or the strategy must improve","The RTO should always equal the RPO","Backups are unnecessary if an RTO exists","The BIA should be deleted"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The recovery strategy cannot meet the stated objective, so the RTO is unrealistic or the strategy must improve</strong> — if the achievable restore time exceeds the RTO, there is a gap between the requirement and the capability that must be closed by either revising the objective or investing in a faster recovery strategy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The RTO should always equal the RPO</b>: is false; they measure different things (time to restore versus data loss).</span><span class='qd'><b>Backups are unnecessary if an RTO exists</b>: is incorrect and dangerous reasoning.</span><span class='qd'><b>The BIA should be deleted</b>: discards the very analysis needed to manage the gap.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-072","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing continuity metrics. Which term represents the total time a business function can be unavailable before the organization suffers unacceptable consequences?","options":["Service delivery objective (SDO)","Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD/MTO)","Mean time between failures (MTBF)","Recovery point objective (RPO)"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Maximum tolerable downtime (MTD/MTO)</strong> — the MTD (also called maximum tolerable outage) is the greatest length of time a function can be down before the impact becomes unacceptable, and the RTO must be set within it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Service delivery objective (SDO)</b>: is the level of service to be reached during recovery, not the maximum outage tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mean time between failures (MTBF)</b>: is a reliability metric for hardware, not a downtime tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Recovery point objective (RPO)</b>: addresses acceptable data loss, not downtime tolerance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-073","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews how the organization prioritized systems for recovery. Which BIA output MOST directly drives that prioritization?","options":["The number of monitors per desk","The color of the server chassis","The brand of the coffee machine","The criticality ranking of business processes and their supporting systems"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The criticality ranking of business processes and their supporting systems</strong> — the BIA ranks processes by impact of disruption, and that criticality ranking drives the order and resources for recovery, ensuring the most vital functions are restored first.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The color of the server chassis</b>: is cosmetic and irrelevant to recovery priority.</span><span class='qd'><b>The brand of the coffee machine</b>: has no bearing on business criticality.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of monitors per desk</b>: does not determine process importance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-074","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds that the BIA was performed solely by the IT department without input from business process owners. What is the MOST significant concern?","options":["Business impacts and criticality may be misjudged because those who own the processes were not consulted","IT will finish the BIA faster","The BIA document will be shorter","Fewer meetings will be required"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Business impacts and criticality may be misjudged because those who own the processes were not consulted</strong> — the BIA depends on business knowledge of process value, dependencies, and tolerances; excluding process owners risks incorrect criticality rankings and flawed recovery objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>IT will finish the BIA faster</b>: prioritizes speed over accuracy and is not a benefit.</span><span class='qd'><b>The BIA document will be shorter</b>: brevity is not the goal and does not offset missing input.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fewer meetings will be required</b>: is a convenience that undermines the analysis quality.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-075","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is assessing system resilience. Which configuration BEST eliminates a single point of failure for a critical server?","options":["A single server with a faster CPU","A clustered/redundant pair with automatic failover","A single server with a brighter status light","A single server with a longer hostname"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A clustered/redundant pair with automatic failover</strong> — clustering two or more servers with automatic failover ensures that if one node fails, another takes over, removing the single point of failure and preserving availability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single server with a faster CPU</b>: is still one server and remains a single point of failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single server with a brighter status light</b>: provides no redundancy.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single server with a longer hostname</b>: is irrelevant to resilience.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-076","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing storage resilience. Which RAID level provides fault tolerance through mirroring, duplicating data on two drives?","options":["JBOD","RAID 0","RAID 1","No RAID"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>RAID 1</strong> — RAID 1 mirrors data across two drives, so if one disk fails the mirror continues to serve the data, providing fault tolerance through duplication.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>RAID 0</b>: stripes data for performance with no redundancy, so a single drive failure loses all data.</span><span class='qd'><b>JBOD</b>: (just a bunch of disks) presents drives independently with no fault tolerance.</span><span class='qd'><b>No RAID</b>: offers no redundancy at all.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-077","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing an array configured as RAID 5. Which statement BEST describes its resilience characteristic?","options":["It mirrors every drive twice for triple redundancy","It uses distributed parity and can tolerate the loss of one drive","It provides no fault tolerance whatsoever","It requires exactly two drives and no parity"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It uses distributed parity and can tolerate the loss of one drive</strong> — RAID 5 stripes data with parity distributed across all drives, allowing the array to reconstruct data and keep running after a single drive failure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It mirrors every drive twice for triple redundancy</b>: describes a mirroring scheme, not RAID 5's single-parity design.</span><span class='qd'><b>It provides no fault tolerance whatsoever</b>: is false; RAID 5 tolerates one disk failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires exactly two drives and no parity</b>: is incorrect; RAID 5 needs at least three drives and uses parity.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-078","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a web tier that spreads incoming requests across several identical servers so that failure of one does not stop the service. Which technique is described?","options":["Tape rotation","Data normalization","Load balancing across redundant nodes","Single-threading"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Load balancing across redundant nodes</strong> — distributing requests across multiple redundant servers both improves capacity and provides resilience, since the loss of one node is absorbed by the others.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data normalization</b>: is a database design method, not a traffic-distribution technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tape rotation</b>: is a backup-media practice unrelated to live request handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>Single-threading</b>: processes one task at a time and reduces, rather than improves, resilience.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-079","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates failover testing. Why is periodic failover testing important even when redundant systems are in place?","options":["To make the network cables shorter","Because redundant systems never work without testing on the first try only","To increase electricity consumption","To confirm the standby actually takes over correctly, since untested failover may fail when needed"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>To confirm the standby actually takes over correctly, since untested failover may fail when needed</strong> — redundancy only helps if the failover mechanism works in practice; periodic testing validates that the standby assumes the load correctly rather than failing silently during a real event.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Because redundant systems never work without testing on the first try only</b>: is a garbled overstatement, not the sound reason.</span><span class='qd'><b>To increase electricity consumption</b>: is not a purpose of testing.</span><span class='qd'><b>To make the network cables shorter</b>: is irrelevant.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-080","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds that a 'redundant' database cluster shares a single storage array, power feed, and network switch. What is the MOST significant resilience weakness?","options":["Shared dependencies remain single points of failure that can take down the whole cluster","The cluster nodes have different serial numbers","The cluster uses too little electricity","The nodes are labeled with stickers"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Shared dependencies remain single points of failure that can take down the whole cluster</strong> — clustering the servers does not remove shared underlying components; a failure of the common storage, power, or switch can bring down every node, defeating the intended redundancy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The cluster nodes have different serial numbers</b>: is normal and irrelevant to resilience.</span><span class='qd'><b>The cluster uses too little electricity</b>: is not a resilience issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>The nodes are labeled with stickers</b>: is a cosmetic detail.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-081","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing backup types. Which backup copies ALL selected data every time it runs, regardless of prior backups?","options":["A full backup","An incremental backup","A differential backup","A transaction-log backup"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A full backup</strong> — a full backup copies all selected data each time, providing the most complete single restore source but taking the most time and space.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>An incremental backup</b>: copies only data changed since the last backup of any type, not everything.</span><span class='qd'><b>A differential backup</b>: copies only data changed since the last full backup, not everything.</span><span class='qd'><b>A transaction-log backup</b>: captures database log records, not all selected data.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-082","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor compares backup strategies. Which combination generally provides the FASTEST restore because only two sets are needed?","options":["A full backup plus every incremental backup since the full","A full backup plus the latest differential backup","Only incremental backups with no full backup","Only transaction logs with no full backup"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A full backup plus the latest differential backup</strong> — restoring from a full plus a single most-recent differential requires only two backup sets, making recovery simpler and typically faster than replaying many incrementals.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A full backup plus every incremental backup since the full</b>: requires restoring the full and each incremental in order, which is slower and more error-prone.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only incremental backups with no full backup</b>: cannot restore because there is no complete baseline.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only transaction logs with no full backup</b>: lacks a base image to apply the logs against.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-083","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a Grandfather-Father-Son (GFS) scheme. What does GFS PRIMARILY provide?","options":["A way to normalize database tables","A method to encrypt the office Wi-Fi","A rotation of daily, weekly, and monthly backup media for retention and recovery flexibility","A load-balancing algorithm"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A rotation of daily, weekly, and monthly backup media for retention and recovery flexibility</strong> — GFS rotates media across daily (son), weekly (father), and monthly (grandfather) cycles, balancing media reuse with the ability to recover from various points in time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A method to encrypt the office Wi-Fi</b>: is a network-security control, not a backup rotation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A way to normalize database tables</b>: is a data-design technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>A load-balancing algorithm</b>: distributes traffic, unrelated to media rotation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-084","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor notes that backup tapes are stored in the same server room as the systems they protect. What is the PRIMARY risk?","options":["The room will be too tidy","The tapes will be too easy to label","Restores will be too fast","A single disaster affecting the room could destroy both the systems and their backups"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A single disaster affecting the room could destroy both the systems and their backups</strong> — colocating backups with the production systems means a fire, flood, or other localized disaster can wipe out both, defeating the purpose of the backup; offsite storage mitigates this.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The tapes will be too easy to label</b>: is not a risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Restores will be too fast</b>: is a benefit, not a risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>The room will be too tidy</b>: is irrelevant.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-085","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a strategy that electronically transmits backup data to a remote location as it is created. Which technique is described?","options":["Printing the data to paper","Manual tape hand-carry once a year","Electronic vaulting / remote journaling","Deleting data to save space"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Electronic vaulting / remote journaling</strong> — electronic vaulting and remote journaling transmit backup data or transaction journals to an offsite location electronically, reducing data loss and eliminating reliance on slow physical media transport.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual tape hand-carry once a year</b>: is slow, infrequent, and would leave a large data-loss window.</span><span class='qd'><b>Printing the data to paper</b>: is not a practical electronic backup method.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting data to save space</b>: destroys data rather than protecting it.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-086","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds that backups run successfully every night but restores have never been tested. What is the MOST significant concern?","options":["The tapes are stored offsite","The backup jobs finish too quickly","The backups use encryption","The organization has no assurance the backups are actually recoverable when needed"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The organization has no assurance the backups are actually recoverable when needed</strong> — a successful backup job does not guarantee the data can be restored; media corruption, incomplete sets, or process errors surface only during a restore test, so untested backups provide false confidence.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The backup jobs finish too quickly</b>: is not inherently a problem.</span><span class='qd'><b>The backups use encryption</b>: is a good practice, not a concern (assuming keys are managed).</span><span class='qd'><b>The tapes are stored offsite</b>: is a strength that supports resilience.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-087","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing the business continuity plan (BCP). On which analysis should the BCP PRIMARILY be based?","options":["The business impact analysis (BIA)","The office seating chart","The vendor's marketing brochure","The annual holiday calendar"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The business impact analysis (BIA)</strong> — the BIA identifies critical processes, impacts, and recovery objectives, and the BCP is built on those findings to ensure continuity efforts focus on what matters most.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The office seating chart</b>: is a facilities layout, not a basis for continuity planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>The vendor's marketing brochure</b>: is promotional material, not an analysis of business impact.</span><span class='qd'><b>The annual holiday calendar</b>: lists dates and is irrelevant to continuity priorities.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-088","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews BCP roles. What is the PRIMARY purpose of naming and training designated recovery teams in advance?","options":["To increase the size of the org chart","To ensure responsibilities are clear and people can act quickly during a disruption","To reduce the number of backups needed","To eliminate the need for a plan document"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To ensure responsibilities are clear and people can act quickly during a disruption</strong> — pre-assigned, trained recovery teams know their roles and can execute the plan without confusion when a real event occurs, reducing response time and errors.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To increase the size of the org chart</b>: is not a purpose of continuity planning.</span><span class='qd'><b>To reduce the number of backups needed</b>: is unrelated to team assignment.</span><span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for a plan document</b>: is false; teams and the documented plan work together.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-089","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a BCP that was written two years ago and never updated despite major reorganizations and system changes. What is the PRIMARY concern?","options":["The plan was reviewed once","The plan document is too long","The plan uses a modern font","The plan may be inaccurate and fail when invoked because it no longer reflects the environment"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The plan may be inaccurate and fail when invoked because it no longer reflects the environment</strong> — a continuity plan must be maintained; outdated contacts, systems, and processes mean the plan could fail at the moment it is needed most.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The plan document is too long</b>: length is not the core issue; accuracy is.</span><span class='qd'><b>The plan uses a modern font</b>: is a cosmetic detail.</span><span class='qd'><b>The plan was reviewed once</b>: a single past review does not address the current staleness.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-090","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor wants to evaluate whether a BCP will work without disrupting operations, by having participants talk through their roles in a meeting. Which test type is this?","options":["A structured walk-through (tabletop) test","A full-interruption test","A parallel test with live cutover","A surprise shutdown of production"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A structured walk-through (tabletop) test</strong> — in a walk-through or tabletop exercise, team members discuss and verify their roles and the plan steps in a meeting, validating the plan without touching production systems.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A full-interruption test</b>: actually shuts down production, which is far more disruptive than a discussion.</span><span class='qd'><b>A parallel test with live cutover</b>: runs recovery systems alongside production, going beyond a talk-through.</span><span class='qd'><b>A surprise shutdown of production</b>: is disruptive and not a discussion-based test.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-091","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is asked which BCP test provides the HIGHEST level of assurance that recovery will actually work, accepting that it carries the greatest operational risk. Which test is it?","options":["A checklist review","A full-interruption test","A structured walk-through","A tabletop discussion"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A full-interruption test</strong> — a full-interruption test halts production and runs entirely on recovery capabilities, providing the most realistic and highest-assurance validation while carrying the greatest risk of actual business disruption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A checklist review</b>: only verifies that plan elements exist and gives low assurance of actual recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>A structured walk-through</b>: discusses roles but does not exercise real recovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>A tabletop discussion</b>: is scenario talk-through with no live execution, so assurance is limited.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-092","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor is reviewing disaster recovery site options. Which site is fully equipped with hardware, software, and current data so it can take over almost immediately?","options":["A warm site","A cold site","A hot site","A reciprocal agreement"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A hot site</strong> — a hot site is fully configured with equipment, software, and near-current data, enabling operations to resume with minimal delay after a disaster.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A cold site</b>: provides only space and utilities, so it takes the longest to bring online.</span><span class='qd'><b>A warm site</b>: has some hardware but not current data, requiring more setup than a hot site.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reciprocal agreement</b>: relies on another organization's spare capacity and is not a dedicated ready site.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-093","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"easy","q":"An IS auditor reviews a DR arrangement consisting of an empty facility with power, cooling, and network connectivity but no installed computing equipment. Which site type is this?","options":["A hot site","A cold site","A mobile site","A mirrored site"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A cold site</strong> — a cold site provides the physical environment (space, power, cooling, connectivity) but no pre-installed systems, so it is the least expensive but slowest option to activate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A hot site</b>: is fully equipped and ready, the opposite of an empty facility.</span><span class='qd'><b>A mobile site</b>: is a transportable unit brought to a location, not a fixed empty building.</span><span class='qd'><b>A mirrored site</b>: is a fully redundant duplicate running in parallel, far beyond an empty shell.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-094","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor evaluates a recovery strategy based on a reciprocal agreement with a similar organization. What is the PRIMARY weakness of this approach?","options":["It guarantees instant recovery with no testing","It is always the most expensive option available","The partner may lack sufficient spare capacity or compatible systems when a disaster actually occurs","It removes the need for any backups"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The partner may lack sufficient spare capacity or compatible systems when a disaster actually occurs</strong> — reciprocal agreements depend on the partner having free capacity and compatible technology at the time of need, which is uncertain, especially in a regional disaster affecting both parties.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is always the most expensive option available</b>: is false; reciprocal agreements are often low-cost.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees instant recovery with no testing</b>: is incorrect; recovery is uncertain and testing is difficult.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for any backups</b>: is wrong; backups are still essential.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-095","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a DRP test in which recovery systems are activated and run alongside production, processing the same data to compare results, without switching off production. Which test type is this?","options":["A structured walk-through","A full-interruption test","A checklist review","A parallel test"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A parallel test</strong> — in a parallel test, recovery systems are brought up and run concurrently with production so results can be compared, validating recovery capability without taking production offline.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A full-interruption test</b>: shuts down production, whereas a parallel test keeps it running.</span><span class='qd'><b>A checklist review</b>: only verifies the plan on paper, with no system activation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A structured walk-through</b>: is a discussion, not a live parallel run.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-096","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a DR strategy that uses a transportable, self-contained unit driven to a location to provide computing facilities after a disaster. Which option is described?","options":["A mobile site","A cold site","A reciprocal agreement","A hot site"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A mobile site</strong> — a mobile site is a transportable, self-contained recovery facility (often a trailer) that can be relocated to where it is needed, providing flexibility when a fixed site is unavailable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A cold site</b>: is a fixed empty building, not transportable.</span><span class='qd'><b>A reciprocal agreement</b>: relies on a partner's premises, not a movable unit.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hot site</b>: is typically a fixed, fully equipped facility, not a mobile unit.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-097","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor is comparing DRP test types by cost and disruption. Which test is the LEAST disruptive and lowest cost while still verifying the plan's contents?","options":["A checklist (desk-check) review","A parallel test","A full-interruption test","A simulation with live systems"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A checklist (desk-check) review</strong> — a checklist review has recovery team members verify that plan components (contacts, resources, procedures) are complete and current, providing basic assurance at the lowest cost and disruption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A parallel test</b>: activates recovery systems and is more costly and involved than a paper review.</span><span class='qd'><b>A full-interruption test</b>: is the most disruptive and costly test.</span><span class='qd'><b>A simulation with live systems</b>: exercises a scenario and is more involved than a checklist.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-098","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor finds a DRP that specifies a hot site but the organization's RPO is near-zero and backups are shipped to the site only weekly. What is the MOST significant gap?","options":["The hot site is unnecessary if backups exist","The weekly data feed cannot meet a near-zero RPO, so recent data would be lost despite the hot site","A near-zero RPO means no site is needed","Weekly backups always satisfy any RPO"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The weekly data feed cannot meet a near-zero RPO, so recent data would be lost despite the hot site</strong> — a hot site addresses fast resumption (RTO), but a near-zero RPO requires near-continuous data replication; weekly shipments would leave up to a week of data unrecoverable, so the data strategy does not match the objective.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The hot site is unnecessary if backups exist</b>: confuses fast resumption with data currency and misjudges the site's role.</span><span class='qd'><b>A near-zero RPO means no site is needed</b>: is illogical; a recovery site is still required.</span><span class='qd'><b>Weekly backups always satisfy any RPO</b>: is false; frequency must match the RPO.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-099","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"medium","q":"An IS auditor reviews a DRP exercise in which participants respond to a scripted disaster scenario and enact response steps in a controlled setting without affecting production. Which test type BEST describes this?","options":["A full-interruption test","A checklist review","A simulation test","A parallel cutover"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A simulation test</strong> — a simulation exercises the team against a realistic scripted scenario, having them carry out response and recovery actions in a controlled way without impacting live production, providing more assurance than a paper review.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A checklist review</b>: merely verifies plan contents and does not enact a scenario.</span><span class='qd'><b>A full-interruption test</b>: actually takes production offline, unlike a controlled simulation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A parallel cutover</b>: runs recovery systems alongside production, which goes beyond a scenario simulation.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-100","domain":4,"obj":"4B5","diff":"hard","q":"An IS auditor is asked what should be done FIRST after a DRP test uncovers significant gaps. Which action is MOST appropriate?","options":["Cancel all future tests to save effort","Discard the DRP because it failed the test","Conceal the results to avoid alarming management","Document the deficiencies and update the plan, then re-test the corrected areas"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Document the deficiencies and update the plan, then re-test the corrected areas</strong> — the value of testing is in learning; deficiencies should be recorded, the plan corrected, and the fixes validated by re-testing so the DRP steadily improves.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Discard the DRP because it failed the test</b>: throws away a plan that should be refined, not abandoned.</span><span class='qd'><b>Conceal the results to avoid alarming management</b>: hides risk and violates audit and governance principles.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cancel all future tests to save effort</b>: removes the very mechanism that surfaces and corrects weaknesses.</span>"}
]);
